Stanley</attrValue></attribute><attribute><attrName>DC_Description__c</attrName><attrType>text</attrType><attrValue>One of the world's top investment banks, Morgan Stanley serves up a smorgasbord of financial services through four separate units. In addition to traditional corporate investment banking services such as underwriting and mergers and acquisitions assistance, the firm offers full-service retail brokerage and premium services for wealthy individuals. Its Investment Management unit provides both individuals and institutions with investment products and services, while the Credit Services division oversees its Discover credit card business through subsidiary Discover Financial Services.

Morgan Stanley has sought to broaden its focus beyond the world of IPOs, M&As, and other pillars of corporate finance. The firm has counted on its breadth of services -- along with cutting some 4,500 jobs in recent years -- to see it through tough competition and economic downturns. Now, like others on the Street, the company is benefiting from investors returning to the market and an upswing in IPOs -- including the one for search engine Google. Morgan Stanley was tapped as one of two lead underwriters for the much-anticipated offering, (Credit Suisse First Boston was the other). 

Morgan Stanley's business comprises four segments: Institutional Securities (traditional investment banking services, institutional sales, and research); Individual Investor (retail brokerage, financial planning and wealth management); Investment Management (mutual funds and other investment vehicles); and Credit Services (Discover Card and insurance).

While the company has been spared some of the controversies plaguing its competitors in recent years, it was one of several firms included in the monumental $1.4 billion settlement with the SEC over alleged conflicts-of-interest between the banks' research and I-banking functions. Morgan Stanley was fined $50 million and ordered to pay an additional $75 million to provide independent research for investors.

Morgan Stanley's research also came under fire when French luxury goods maker LVMH (the company behind such brands as Christian Dior, Louis Vuitton, and Moet & Chandon) accused the firm of publishing inaccurate information that not only damaged its reputation, but was biased toward rival Gucci. A French court awarded LVMH $38.5 million in damages; Morgan Stanley plans to appeal.

When the regulatory scrutiny shifted to the mutual fund industry, Morgan Stanley was charged with failing to adequately disclose the incentives its brokers and managers received for selling certain funds. In November 2003, the firm agreed to pay a $50 million fine and adopt a "plain English" approach to informing investors about its product fees and broker compensation.

Finally, in mid-2004 the firm agreed to pay $54 million to settle a sex discrimination lawsuit filed on behalf of more than 300 female employees who claimed they were denied promotions and salary raises.

A slump in revenues domestically led the firm to look toward Europe to fuel its fortunes, but it faced the same sluggish economy abroad. Meanwhile, Morgan Stanley has been trying to build its Discover card business -- which has some 50 million cardmember accounts -- by adding more than 600,000 new merchant locations in 2003.

In mid-2004 Morgan Stanley spun off its Morgan Stanley Capital Partners unit to create an independent private equity firm. The new company, Metalmark Capital, is led by principals from the Capital Partners business.

Also in 2004, the company's Morgan Stanley Capital International (MSCI) unit acquired Barra, Inc., a California-based provider of risk management software. Barra is being combined with MSCI to form MSCI
